---
import Primer from '../../layouts/Primer.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';
---
<Primer
  title="What Actually Changes"
  eyebrow="A Primer on Matter Models · Chapter Seven"
  deck="A fast, near-universal potential moves the bottleneck. It does not remove it — and which outcomes were ever gated by the potential is a sharper question than it looks."
  running="Ch. 7 — What Actually Changes"
  prev={{ href: url('/primer/at-inference-time'), label: 'At Inference Time' }}
>
  <p class="lead">
    The promise is easy to state. Make the energy of a set of atoms cheap and accurate everywhere,
    and the world of materials and molecules opens. The trouble is in the quiet word
    <em>everywhere</em>, and in a hidden assumption underneath the whole sentence: that the energy
    surface was the thing standing in the way of the outcome you cared about.
  </p>

  <p>
    For most headline outcomes it was not. A drug, a battery, a catalyst, a better alloy — each is
    the end of a long pipeline, and the energy evaluation is one station on it. Make that station
    free and the pipeline does not finish; the queue simply backs up at the next station. So the
    useful question is not "what does a universal potential unlock," but the narrower and more
    honest one: which outcomes were actually gated by the potential energy surface, and which only
    look like they were.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 1</span>The bottleneck moves; it does not vanish</h2>

  <p>
    Picture the path from an idea to a thing that works as a line of stations. First, decide what to
    even make — pick a composition, a structure, a molecule. Then simulate it: relax it, check that
    it holds together, predict how it behaves. Then synthesize it in a lab. Then measure the real
    article and find out whether the simulation told the truth. The potential lives entirely in the
    second station.
  </p>

  <p>
    A fast, accurate potential shrinks that second station, sometimes by orders of magnitude — a
    relaxation that was hours of DFT becomes seconds. But shrinking one station only matters to the
    whole line if it was the slow one. For most real programs the slow stations are elsewhere:
    deciding what to make (the <strong>inverse problem</strong> — you can score a candidate far
    faster than you can think of the right candidate), and making and measuring it (synthesis and
    experimental validation, which run at the speed of furnaces and instruments, not GPUs). Free
    energy evaluation relocates the rate limiter to those stations; it does not abolish it.
  </p>

