  </figure>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 2</span>The carve that cuts the materials world in half</h2>

  <p>
    There is a second, harder limit, and Chapter 5 already drew it. A forward energy model gives you
    the geometry of the energy surface and everything that is a derivative of it: stable structures,
    whether a phase holds together, the kinetics — rates and pathways — of how atoms move and ions migrate, the mechanical
    response to a load, the thermal behavior. What it does not give you is anything that lives in the
    electronic spectrum — band gaps, optical absorption, magnetism, superconductivity. Those are
    Tier 3, and an energy model is permanently silent on them.
  </p>

  <p>
    That silence carves the materials world roughly in half, and along an awkward seam. The
    functional materials people most romanticize are useful for exactly the electronic-structure
    reasons a potential cannot speak to. A solar cell absorbs light because of its band gap. A
    transistor switches because of its band structure. An LED emits at a color set by its gap; a
    magnet, a superconductor — all electronic facts. For these a forward potential can relax the
    structure and check that it is stable, then it must hand off. It cannot tell you the property you
    actually wanted.
  </p>

  <p>
    Where a fast universal potential comes closest to decisive is the other half — materials whose
    worth is set by structure, stability, ion transport, mechanics, or heat: structural alloys and
    refractory ceramics, solid-state electrolytes and battery interfaces, catalysts, thermal-management
    materials. This is a real and important slice. It is also a slice, and not the one most
    "AI discovers new materials" press releases are quietly pointing at.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
