  <h2><span class="num">§ 3</span>The strongest cases</h2>

  <p>
    The first is any problem genuinely gated by the cost of mapping a large energy landscape, and the
    cleanest example is <strong>heterogeneous catalysis</strong> — a reaction sped along by a solid
    surface. To find a good catalyst you must know how strongly a molecule sticks to a surface (its
    adsorption energy) and how high the barrier is for the reaction step, and you must know these
    across a combinatorial grid: every composition, crossed with every crystal facet, crossed with
    every adsorbate and intermediate. That grid is enormous, each cell of it is an energy-surface
    question, and DFT is too slow to fill it. These are exactly the quantities a fast potential is
    fit to supply, and it is why the Open Catalyst effort exists. Whether that is sufficient to
    screen a good catalyst depends on the system — selectivity involves competing pathways that are
    harder to rank — but for the screening step it is the right tool, and the motivation, at least,
    points at real stakes: cheaper catalysts for green hydrogen, ammonia synthesis, carbon-dioxide
    reduction, fuel cells.
  </p>

  <p>
    The second is subtler: the potential as a
    scientific <strong>instrument</strong>. A million atoms, simulated for a microsecond, at near
    quantum accuracy, lets you watch processes that were invisible from both sides at once — too fast
    and too small for experiment to catch, too expensive for honest DFT to reach. A crystal nucleus
    forming out of a melt. The protective film growing on a battery electrode in its first cycles.
    Dislocations gliding and a crack running through a metal under load. A phase transforming;
    water meeting a solid surface; matter squeezed to the pressures inside a planet. The payoff here
    is not a product but understanding — mechanism you could not see before.
  </p>

  <div class="aside">
    <span class="aside-label">On instruments</span>
    A better telescope did not, on the day it was built, discover a planet. It made a class of
    observations possible, and the discoveries followed over years as people looked. The
    quantum-accurate, million-atom simulation is that kind of instrument: its value is the
    observations it newly permits, not a single result you can name in advance.
  </div>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 4</span>The weakest case</h2>

  <p>
    The case that gets oversold is drug discovery, and it is worth saying why plainly. A potential
    can improve the energetics that feed a binding-affinity calculation — how tightly a candidate
    molecule grips its protein target, the relative energies of a molecule's shapes (its conformers)
    and its protonation states (whether the molecule has picked up or lost a hydrogen ion in
    solution). These are accuracy upgrades to free-energy methods, and they are welcome.
  </p>

  <p>
    But the difficulty in protein–ligand binding is not the accuracy of a single energy. It is
    sampling — a flexible molecule and a flexible protein each writhe through an astronomical number
    of shapes, and the answer is an average over all of them — and it is sheer system scale. A more
    accurate energy at one geometry does little for a problem whose hardness is in counting the
    geometries. The recent leap in predicting protein structure came from a different lineage
    entirely, one that learned from a database of known structures rather than from the physics of
    the energy surface. And the things that actually sink drug programs — choosing the right target
    in the first place, whether the body absorbs and tolerates the compound, failure in the
    clinic — do not touch atoms at all. The contribution here is incremental, not transformative.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 5</span>The deepest objections</h2>

  <p>
    Two objections cut to the bone, and an honest accounting has to sit with them.
  </p>

  <p>
    The first is about where a model can be trusted. Discovery means going where the data is not —
    that is what makes it discovery. But a potential is most accurate exactly where you least need
    it: near known, mostly-stable chemistry, densely covered by its training set. It is least
    reliable in the exotic, far-from-equilibrium, transition-state regions where genuine novelty
    lives — and there even the uncertainty flag of Chapter 6 is little help, being itself
    extrapolated, and so least trustworthy exactly where you most need it. The honest engineering
    reply is <strong>dynamic</strong> fine-tuning — the fine-tuning of Chapter 4, done on the fly:
    when you stray off the map, generate fresh DFT reference points for the new region and patch the
    model as you go. It works. But notice what it costs: if you must compute new reference data for
    each new system, the DFT expense you were trying to escape walks quietly back in.
  </p>

  <p>
    The second is about the ceiling, and it never moves. The word <strong>universal</strong> is
    carrying enormous weight in these promises, and a potential's accuracy is still bounded by its
    reference method. A perfect emulator of DFT inherits DFT's errors exactly. For strongly
    correlated systems — materials where the electrons interact so tightly that the standard DFT
    approximation breaks down, as in many transition-metal oxides — for the weak dispersion forces
    that hold soft matter together, for reaction barriers, for anything excited out of its ground
    state, DFT itself is often not good enough — so
    a flawless DFT emulator is, in those very places, not good enough either. And even a perfect,
    instant forward model answers only "how good is this candidate," never "what should I make."
    Generative models that propose candidates help with that inverse problem, but they propose
    novel structures — out of distribution by construction — and then trustworthiness on the
    unfamiliar is the whole game over again.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 6</span>The honest answer</h2>

  <p>
    So here is the accounting, with no thumb on the scale. The forward-simulation and triage stage
    gets cheap and quantum-accurate; that much is real and already arriving. The rate limiter moves
    downstream, to closing the loop with synthesis and experiment. The largest single multiplier is
    therefore not a better potential sitting in isolation — it is a fast potential
    <strong>coupled tightly to an autonomous experiment</strong>, a lab that proposes, simulates,
    makes, measures, and feeds the result back without waiting on a human at each step. Computation
    triages; the robot lab adjudicates; the disagreements become tomorrow's training data.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
